      '\n- any three of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ electrons donated by reduced NAD and FAD OR NADH and FADH at the beginning of the electron transport chain\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ electrons are passed along electron carriers\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ final electron acceptor is oxygen OR 1/2 O2  \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ excess hydrogen ions OR protons, from intermembrane space OR coenzymes OR reduced NAD OR reduced FAD found in matrix OR accumulate in the matrix\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ hydrogen ions OR protons react with oxygen to form water\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ 4e- + 4H+ + O2 → 2H2O OR 4 electrons + 4 protons + 1 molecule of oxygen →  2 molecules of water\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nElectrons donated by reduced NAD and FAD at the beginning of the electron transport chain ($\\checkmark$) are passed along electron carriers ($\\checkmark$), with the final electron acceptor being oxygen ($\\checkmark$). Hydrogen ions in the matrix react with oxygen to form water ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- any five of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ polar so can form hydrogen bonds \t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ strong cohesive forces between water molecules help pull other water molecules up the xylem\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ strong adhesive properties mean water can stick to lignin OR cellulose OR inside of the xylem\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ cohesion and adhesion work together to enable capillary action OR allow water to move against gravity in xylem vessels\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ evaporation from leaves creates a negative pressure OR tension in the xylem vessels, which helps to “pull” more water up the plant\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ cohesion-tension theory OR cohesive forces between water molecules and the tension created in the xylem vessels create a continuous column of water\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ high latent heat of vaporisation so water can evaporate from the stomata and stimulate the transpiration stream\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ low viscosity, so can flow easily through small pores in the plant\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ root pressure results from the active pumping of ions into the root cells, creating an osmotic gradient that causes water to enter the roots\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>5 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nWater is able to move around a plant because it is polar, so hydrogen bonds can form ($\\checkmark$) between different water molecules, which allow them to be cohesive so they can stick together to be pulled up the xylem ($\\checkmark$) at low pressure. Water molecules are adhesive which allows them to stick to cellulose in the plant ($\\checkmark$). The cohesion and adhesion work together to enable capillary action up the xylem vessels ($\\checkmark$).  Water has a high latent heat of vaporisation, so water can evaporate from the stomata and maintain the transpiration stream ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- any seven of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ sources are where carbohydrates are synthesised \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ sinks are where carbohydrates are utilised\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ sucrose and H+ are co-transported into the companion cells (in apoplastic route) near the source\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ sucrose concentration increases in the companion cells\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ sucrose diffuses into sieve tube via plasmodesmata\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ sucrose diffuses through cytoplasm of neighbouring cells, via plasmodesmata into phloem (in symplastic route)\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the increase in concentration of carbohydrates OR sucrose OR decrease in solute potential results in water flowing into the phloem via osmosis\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ raises the hydrostatic pressure in the sieve tube elements near the source cell\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ organic compounds, OR carbohydrates OR named example, are unloaded from phloem, OR sieve tubes near the sink\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ decreases the solute concentration (in sieve tubes at sinks)\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ water moves out of the sieve tubes reducing hydrostatic pressure <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ water OR sap containing the sucrose OR carbohydrates moves down the hydrostatic pressure gradient towards the sink\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>7 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nSources are where carbohydrates are synthesised in plants, such as photosynthesising leaves ($\\checkmark$) and sinks are where carbohydrates are used, such as growing shoots ($\\checkmark$). In plants, sucrose and H+ are co-transported into companion cells near the source ($\\checkmark$), this causes the sucrose concentration to increase in companion cells ($\\checkmark$). Sucrose then diffuses into sieve tubes via plasmodesmata ($\\checkmark$) and then diffuses through the cytoplasm of neighbouring cells, into the phloem ($\\checkmark$). This causes water to move into the phloem via osmosis from the xylem ($\\checkmark$), raising the hydrostatic pressure ($\\checkmark$). At the sink, the carbohydrates are unloaded from the phloem ($\\checkmark$), decreasing the solute concentration ($\\checkmark$), water follows, thereby reducing hydrostatic pressure ($\\checkmark$). The sap containing the carbohydrates move down the hydrostatic pressure gradient towards the sink ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\nA quality mark is awarded if each part of the question (a, b, c) is answered to earn at least half of the points available, answers do not require re-reading to be understood, and there are almost no errors and little irrelevant information. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n',
