    selection: 'Selection A',
    type: 'SAQ',
    title: 'Question 28',
    content:
      'The diagram below shows the structure of DNA nucleotides.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/d2ec462e-9faf-4026-9eb2-c56d6db3f2b2/images/74d13066-c44a-4c8c-ad4b-36170db36b8a/BI0899A.png)\n\n\n[Source: Adapted from OpenStax Anatomy and Physiology, (2016, May). File:0322 DNA Nucleotides.jpg. Wikimedia commons. Retrieved July 6, 2023, from https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:0322_DNA_Nucleotides.jpg. Copyright under CC-BY-4.0]\n\n- State the component of DNA that is attached at position X.  \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n- Identify the type of bonding shown as dotted lines in the diagram. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n- The 5’ and 3’ linkages in DNA play an important role in replication, transcription and translation.\n  \n  - On the diagram, label the 5’ prime and 3’ prime ends on both strands to show the direction of the DNA.  \t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  - Outline how the processes of transcription and translation occur with regards to the formation of  5’ and 3’ linkages. \t\t\t<span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n\n- Explain how the DNA helix maintains its stability.  \t<span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- Erwin Chargaff’s data on the relative amounts of purine and pyrimidine bases played an important role in determining the structure of DNA.\n  \n  - Outline how Chargaff’s data contributed to our understanding of the structure of DNA.\t  \t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n  - State a proposed model of DNA that was falsified by Chargaff\'s data.\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- \n\n$\\hspace{1em}$ $\\ce{ -> }$ phosphate OR phosphate group\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>1 mark maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n$\\hspace{1em}$ $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \n$\\hspace{1em}$ A phosphate group is found at X ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n- \n\n$\\hspace{1em}$ $\\ce{ -> }$ hydrogen OR hydrogen bonds\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>1 mark maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n$\\hspace{1em}$ $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \n$\\hspace{1em}$ Hydrogen bonding ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n- \n  - \n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ both strands are labelled correctly with 5’ at the available 5th carbon and 3’ at the available 3rd carbon\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>1 mark maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$:\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/d2ec462e-9faf-4026-9eb2-c56d6db3f2b2/images/2506b383-fa8c-4d98-9f33-ad5bce798cdb/BI0899ANSA.png)\n\n\n\n\n\n- \n  - Any two of the following (AT LEAST     ONE from transcription and     ONE from translation):\n\n  transcription\n$\\ce{ -> }$ RNA polymerase adds nucleotides to the 3’ end of the growing mRNA strand\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ RNA polymerase creates the RNA strand in the 5’ to the 3’ direction\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ RNA polymerase reads the DNA template strand in the 3’ to 5’ direction\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the new nucleotides are added to the 3’ end through phosphodiester linkages between the 3’ carbon of the last nucleotide and the phosphate group of the incoming nucleotide\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  translation\n$\\ce{ -> }$ ribosome moves along the mRNA from the 5’ end to the 3’ end\t \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ codons of the mRNA are read from the 5’ end to the 3’ end to add amino acids that form the polypeptide \t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>2 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$:\nIn transcription, RNA polymerase reads the DNA template strand in the 3’ to 5’ direction ($\\checkmark$) and creates the RNA strand in the opposite direction ($\\checkmark$). In translation, the ribosome moves along the mRNA in the 5’ to 3’ direction ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any two of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ purine-to-pyrimidine bonding OR complementary base pairing\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ adenine-thymine OR A-T and cytosine-guanine OR C-G have equal lengths\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ hydrogen bonding between complementary bases  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ hydrophobic interaction between adjacent bases \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ phosphodiester bonds link the 3’ carbon of one deoxyribose sugar to the phosphate group on the 5’ carbon of the next, forming a strong sugar-phosphate backbone\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ by winding around central histone proteins in eukaryotes to form nucleosomes\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>2 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$:\nThe DNA double helix maintains its stability through complementary base pairing of purine to pyrimidine ($\\checkmark$). This base pairing is held together by 2 hydrogen bonds between adenine to thymine and 3 hydrogen bonds ($\\checkmark$) between cytosine and guanine.\n\n\n\n- \n  - Any two of the following:\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ showed the ratio of adenine to thymine and guanine to cytosine are equal <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ showed that the four nucleotide bases are not in repeating sequences OR equally distributed\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ suggested that DNA consists of two complementary strands\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ showed that the composition of DNA varies across diverse life forms\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ helped Watson and Crick in building the double helix shape of their DNA model\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ base pairing data suggested A pairs with T and G pairs with C\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ base pairing data suggested  mechanisms whereby DNA could replicate OR be transcribed\t <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>2 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$:\nChargaff’s data showed that the molar ratio of adenine to thymine and the ratio of guanine to cytosine are close to 1:1 ($\\checkmark$). This data then helped Watson and Crick to deduce that DNA consists of two complementary strands ($\\checkmark$) and is helical in shape ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- \n  - Any one of the following:\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ tetranucleotide hypothesis OR theory of four nucleotide bases in repeating sequence OR repeating tetramer nucleic acid \t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the purely protein-based genetic material\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>1 mark maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$:\nThe tetranucleotide hypothesis ($\\checkmark$) was falsified by Chargaff’s data.\n',
