    content:
      'DNA and RNA are nucleic acids that are essential to all living organisms. ATP is a type of nucleotide.\n\n- Distinguish between ATP and the monomers of DNA in humans. <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Outline the roles of the different types of RNA involved in translation.\t <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Describe the structure of the DNA double helix.  <span class="marks">[8]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Any three of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ ATP contains three phosphate groups WHEREAS each DNA nucleotide contains only one phosphate group \t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ ATP has adenine for a nitrogenous base WHEREAS a DNA nucleotide can contain adenine, cytosine, guanine or thymine\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ a component of ATP is ribose WHEREAS DNA nucleotides have deoxyribose instead\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ ATP stores energy OR provides energy, WHEREAS DNA carries OR transmits genetic information\t  \t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ ATP can perform its function as a single monomer WHEREAS DNA can only perform its function, OR carry genetic material as a polymer\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ ATP is found throughout the cell OR primarily in the cytoplasm OR mitochondria WHEREAS DNA is found primarily in the nucleus OR only found in the nucleus AND mitochondria\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nBoth ATP and DNA molecules are nucleic acids which contain a phosphate group, a sugar and a base. The structural difference between a molecule of ATP and a molecule of DNA is that one ATP molecule contains three phosphate groups whereas one DNA nucleotide contains one phosphate group ($\\checkmark$). In addition, the nitrogenous base in ATP is adenine whereas there are four possible nitrogenous bases in one nucleotide of DNA which are adenine, cytosine, guanine and thymine ($\\checkmark$). The functional difference is that ATP stores energy, whereas DNA carries genetic material ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any four of the following (there must be at least one statement for each of mRNA, tRNA and rRNA to achieve maximum marks):\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ mRNA carries the genetic information from DNA to the ribosome\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ mRNA serves as a template for protein synthesis\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ codons of mRNA  specify positioning of  amino acids along polypeptide OR codons guide the assembly of amino acids into a polypeptide \t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ tRNA molecules carry amino acids to mRNA OR ribosome\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ anticodons on tRNA complementary to codons on mRNA allow amino acids to be positioned correctly along the polypeptide OR anticodons bind to codons to bring corresponding amino acid to the ribosome \t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ rRNA provides the ribosome\'s structural framework OR forms ribosomes\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ rRNA catalyses the formation of peptide bonds between adjacent amino acids \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ rRNA facilitates binding of mRNA and tRNA\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ mRNA, tRNA, and rRNA orchestrate protein synthesis during translation\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>4 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nTogether, mRNA, tRNA, and rRNA orchestrate the process of protein synthesis ($\\checkmark$) during translation. mRNA carries the genetic information from DNA to the ribosome  ($\\checkmark$). Codons on the mRNA specify the positioning of amino acids along the polypeptide chain  ($\\checkmark$). Each tRNA molecule has a specific anticodon sequence that is complementary to a codon on the mRNA  ($\\checkmark$). This base-pairing specificity allows tRNA to bring the corresponding amino acid to the correct position to form the polypeptide  ($\\checkmark$). The rRNA catalyses the formation of peptide bonds between adjacent amino acids  ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any eight of the following: \n(appropriately labelled and correctly drawn DNA segment can be used in the answer)\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ each strand of DNA is a polymer of nucleotides \t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ each strand has a sugar-phosphate backbone\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ four nitrogenous bases A OR adenine AND T OR thymine AND C OR cytosine AND G OR guanine  \t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ two strands are anti-parallel OR parallel but in opposite directions OR one strand is in the 5’ to 3’ direction and the other strand is in the 3’ to 5’ direction\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ strands are twisted OR right-handed and turn into a double helix with around 10 base pairs per turn\t\t  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ nucleotides consist of one phosphate group, one deoxyribose sugar and one nitrogenous base\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ phosphate group is bound to the 5’ carbon of the sugar OR deoxyribose OR pentose   \t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ phosphate group is bound to the 3’ carbon OH group of deoxyribose (of the next nucleotide)\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ covalent OR phosphodiester bond between phosphate and the sugar\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ nitrogenous base OR base is bound to the 1’ carbon of the sugar OR deoxyribose OR pentose sugar \t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ covalent bond between nitrogenous base and deoxyribose OR sugar OR pentose sugar \t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ two strands are held together by hydrogen bonds between nitrogen bases of two nucleotides OR 3 hydrogen bonds between guanine and cytosine OR 2 hydrogen bonds between adenine and thymine\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ complementary base pairing between nitrogenous bases\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ A pairs up with T AND C pairs up with G\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>8 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nDNA is a nucleic acid, also known as a polymer of nucleotides ($\\checkmark$) . Many nucleotides are joined together to form it. One nucleotide consists of three parts; a phosphate group, deoxyribose sugar and a nitrogenous base ($\\checkmark$).\n  One end of the phosphate group is bonded to the 5’ carbon of the deoxyribose sugar ($\\checkmark$). On the other side of the nucleotide, the phosphate group is bonded to the 3’ carbon sugar ($\\checkmark$) of another nucleotide. Both bonds are covalent phosphodiester bonds ($\\checkmark$). Repeated alternating sugar-phosphate bonds form the sugar-phosphate backbone ($\\checkmark$).  The 1’ carbon of the sugar is covalently bonded to the nitrogenous base ($\\checkmark$) also through a condensation reaction to make up one complete nucleotide.\n  DNA is a double helix ($\\checkmark$) in which nitrogenous bases form the centre of the structure, and both strands are held together by hydrogen bonds ($\\checkmark$) between the complementary bases from each strand. A pairs up with T, and C always pairs up with G ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\nA quality mark is awarded if each part of the question (a, b, c) is answered to earn at least half of the points available, answers do not require re-reading to be understood, and there are almost no errors and little irrelevant information. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n',
