    type: 'SAQ',
    title: 'Question 44',
    content:
      '![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/baf04dcc-f4a0-48d2-9a7d-1963add3cf0c/images/19006f6d-bdf7-40b0-a6de-aa5d19c784ed/BI1850.png)\n\n\n[© Revision Village 2024. Created with BioRender.com]\n\n\n- Describe the role of DNA in storing genetic information.\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- Outline the importance of the antiparallel arrangement of DNA strands in the structure of DNA.\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Outline the importance of the diversity of DNA base sequences in the process of evolution. \t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Discuss the importance of the conservation of the genetic code in understanding universal common ancestry. \t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Any two of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ genetic code is stored in the sequence of nucleotide bases OR adenine, thymine, cytosine, guanine\t within the DNA molecule\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ groups of three nucleotides OR bases form codons, which correspond to specific amino acids\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ sequence of codons determines the primary structure of proteins, which controls the organism’s traits and functions\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ double-helix structure ensures stability of genetic information and allows for accurate replication during cell division\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ genetic code is degenerate OR multiple codons can code for same amino acid providing some protection against mutations\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ genes can be turned on or off OR are used when needed OR can be expressed and repressed <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>2 mark maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nDNA stores genetic information in the form of codons, which are sequences of three nucleotide bases ($\\checkmark$) that code for specific amino acids ($\\checkmark$). These codons determine the structure of proteins, which are essential for the organism’s traits and functions ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any three of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ two DNA strands run in opposite directions OR one strand runs 5\' to 3\', while the other runs 3\' to 5\'\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ allows the complementary base pairs OR adenine-thymine AND guanine-cytosine to align properly and form hydrogen bonds\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ hydrogen bonding stabilises the double helix\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ antiparallel strands allow for the twisting of the DNA molecule \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ ensures that the DNA molecule is stable and can store genetic information effectively\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe antiparallel arrangement means that one DNA strand runs 5\' to 3\', while the other runs 3\' to 5\' ($\\checkmark$). This allows the complementary base pairs to align correctly and form hydrogen bonds between adenine-thymine and guanine-cytosine ($\\checkmark$). These hydrogen bonds help stabilise the double helix and allow the DNA to twist into its characteristic structure ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any three of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ leads to genetic variation between individuals within a population\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ provides the basis for natural selection, as certain traits may offer a selective advantage in specific environments\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ Individuals with advantageous traits are more likely to survive and reproduce, passing their favourable alleles OR genes to the next generation <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ over time, advantageous traits become more common, driving evolution and the development of new species\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ allows populations to adapt to changing environments, contributing to species\' survival\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe diversity of DNA base sequences leads to genetic variation between individuals in a population ($\\checkmark$). This variation provides the basis for natural selection, where certain traits offer a selective advantage in specific environments ($\\checkmark$). Over time, individuals with advantageous traits are more likely to survive, reproduce, and pass on their favourable genes ($\\checkmark$), driving the process of evolution and the development of new species.\n\n\n\n- Any two of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ genetic code is nearly universal across all living organisms OR there are only a few minor variations in the genetic code observed in certain species\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ in nearly all organisms the same triplet codons specify the same amino acids\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ universality of the genetic code implies a shared ancestral origin for all organisms \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ used in phylogenetic analysis to reconstruct evolutionary relationships, providing strong evidence for universal common ancestry\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ conservation of the genetic code helps maintain the integrity of proteins OR reduces  risk of mutations that could disrupt essential cellular functions\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ despite evolutionary changes in species, the genetic code remains largely unchanged over time\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>2 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe conservation of the genetic code across all organisms suggests that all life shares a common ancestor, as the same triplet codons specify the same amino acids in all species ($\\checkmark$). This universality indicates that the genetic code has been passed down through generations with little change ($\\checkmark$), providing evidence for universal common ancestry.\n',
