    content:
      'Which of the following statements are reasons that RNA is believed to be the first genetic material?\n\n\n- I.RNA can form spontaneously when nucleotides are presentII.RNA contains ribose as its sugarIII.RNA can function as enzymes\n\n\n\n\n- A.$\\hspace{1em}$ I only\n- B.$\\hspace{1em}$ I and III\n- C.$\\hspace{1em}$ II and III\n- D.$\\hspace{1em}$ I, II and III\n',
    markScheme:
      'B\n\n$\\underline{\\textrm{Explanation}}$: \nRNA is believed to be a potential candidate for the first genetic material due to its ability to form spontaneously from nucleotides (Statement I). RNA molecules, known as ribozymes, can catalyze chemical reactions (Statement III), including their own replication. This is a key reason why RNA is considered the first genetic material—unlike DNA, RNA can both store information and perform enzymatic functions, making it a strong candidate for early life processes.  Choice B is correct.\nChoice A only included Statement I and not III, so it is incorrect.\nWhile it is true that RNA contains ribose as its sugar component (Statement II), the presence of ribose is not a primary reason for RNA being considered the first genetic material. Both RNA and DNA contain sugars in their structures, but the key point in favour of RNA as the first genetic material is its ability to form spontaneously. Choices C and D included Statement II and so are incorrect.',
