    type: 'ERQ',
    title: 'Question 14',
    content:
      '\n- Describe how the primordial soup hypothesis (an aqueous mix of simple organic molecules) explains the origin of carbon compounds on Earth. <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Mitochondria are organelles that are thought to have evolved from early prokaryotes. Discuss whether mitochondria can be considered living or nonliving. <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Discuss the evidence and limitations for the existence of a last universal common ancestor. <span class="marks">[8]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Any three of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ early atmosphere OR oceans contained a mixture of gases OR carbon dioxide AND methane OR water vapour OR ammonia OR hydrogen gas <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ high levels of UV OR ultraviolet light OR electrical discharges OR lightning catalysed reactions in these gases\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ the gases broke down into smaller, highly reactive components\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ the smaller components reacted to form larger carbon compounds OR more complex organic molecules\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ abiogenesis OR chemical evolution\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ in water OR pools OR oceans\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n<span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe primordial soup hypothesis states that billions of years ago, there were much higher levels of UV light on Earth which catalysed reactions in the gases of the early atmosphere ($\\checkmark$). The UV radiation broke down inorganic molecules into smaller, highly reactive components ($\\checkmark$). The smaller, highly reactive components reacted to form larger carbon compounds ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any four of the following:\nAnswers must include at least one argument for living and one argument for non-living to gain full marks\nLiving because…\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ they can replicate independently of the host cell OR carry our binary fission\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ they contain their own ribosomes to make their own proteins\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ they contain their own DNA OR genetic material\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ they can make their own ATP OR release energy from organic molecules OR carry out a series of metabolic reactions independent of the host cell\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ they have their own membranes\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ they can grow larger\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ they can excrete waste OR carbon dioxide\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  Non-living because…\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ they cannot survive independently outside of a host cell\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ the majority of proteins needed for mitochondrial function are synthesised in the host cell\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ they do not regulate homeostasis independently of the host cell\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ they cannot respond to stimuli OR adapt to changing environments\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n<span class="marks">[<strong>4 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nMitochondria can be thought of as non-living because they cannot survive independently outside the host cell ($\\checkmark$) and the majority of proteins needed for mitochondrial function are made in the host cell ($\\checkmark$). However, it could be argued that they are living as they carry out several life processes, such as reproduction, independently of the host cell ($\\checkmark$), and contain their own ribosomes which they use to make their own proteins ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any eight of the following:\nAnswers must include at least one argument in support of a last universal common ancestor (LUCA) and at least one gap in the evidence to gain full marks\n  Evidence that exists for the existence of a last universal common ancestor\n$\\ce{ -> }$ universal genetic code OR all organisms have the same nucleotide bases OR genetic code \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ conserved molecular structures OR all organisms have the same degenerate amino acid code OR the same codons code for the same amino acids in all organisms OR there are highly conserved DNA sequences that are common across many domains of life\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ genomic analysis of fossils shows that there are many similarities in the DNA sequences between modern and extinct organisms\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ specific proteins produced by different organisms can be used interchangeably between species without any major side effects\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ all organisms have a similar process for gene transcription and protein synthesis OR transcription and translation\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ mutations in DNA OR amino acid sequences can be tracked over time and used as a ‘molecular clock’ to estimate the age of the last universal common ancestor\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  Gaps in the evidence for the existence of a last universal common ancestor\n$\\ce{ -> }$ incomplete fossil record makes it difficult to link all species together anatomically\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ very early organisms were unicellular OR made of soft tissues that do not readily fossilise\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ lack of direct fossil evidence for the last universal common ancestor\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ the last universal common ancestor does not exist today\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n<span class="marks">[<strong>8 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe last universal common ancestor (LUCA) is proposed to be the evolutionary link between the abiotic phase of Earth’s history and the biotic phase. It is the last ancestor that links all biological life on Earth. Evidence for the LUCA’s existence comes from the fact that organisms are all biochemically similar; they share the same DNA bases ($\\checkmark$). Furthermore, the same codons code for the same amino acids in all organisms ($\\checkmark$), and all organisms have a similar process for gene transcription and protein synthesis($\\checkmark$). Also, there are some highly conserved sequences across the majority of organisms such as ribosomal RNA which is common across all domains of life ($\\checkmark$). Genomic analysis of fossils also shows that there are many similar DNA sequences between extinct and modern organisms ($\\checkmark$). However, there isn’t a complete fossil record which makes it difficult to link all species anatomically ($\\checkmark$), there is no direct fossil evidence for the existence of the LUCA ($\\checkmark$) and the LUCA does not exist on Earth today ($\\checkmark$).\n',
