    content:
      'Louis Pasteur disproved the theory of spontaneous generation by showing that life did not spontaneously arise from non-living matter but came from existing microorganisms. In his experiment, he set up the following flasks:\nOpen straight-neck flask containing boiled broth.\nSwan-neck flask containing boiled broth (neck allowed air to flow but trapped dust and microbes).\nControl flask containing boiled broth and sealed from the air.\nThe experiment was replicated as shown below:\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/4f264e0a-eabd-4da0-bfbf-912611178311/images/9f2606f0-633f-460c-b9ba-a9599ddfb669/Pasteur%20flask%20RV.png)\n\n\n[ © Revision Village. Created using BioRender.com ]\n\nWhich two flasks would show the presence of microorganisms in the results?\n\n\n\n- A. $\\hspace{1em}$ R and S\n- B. $\\hspace{1em}$ S and Q\n- C. $\\hspace{1em}$ Q and R\n- D. $\\hspace{1em}$ P and Q\n',
