    content:
      'The figure below shows the results of a study on the evolution of multicellularity. Obligate multicellularity means the organism is always multicellular, facultative multicellularity means the organism is usually unicellular but can sometimes form multicellular structures.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/e940829b-1b89-44cf-8a66-34d55df8cf92/images/6b245b5b-8c5e-4ec0-ad11-47b0515ebe5a/Ed2727.png)\n\n\n[Source: Adapted from Fisher, R. (2013). Group Formation, Relatedness, and the Evolution of Multicellularity. Current Biology, 23. Retrieved April 2025  from https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0960982213005678. CC BY 3.0.]\n\nWhat can be deduced from this phylogenetic tree?\n\n\n- I.All mammals are obligately multicellularII.Multicellularity evolved once in eukaryotesIII.All prokaryotes are unicellular\n\n\n\n\n- A.$\\hspace{1em}$ I only\n- B.$\\hspace{1em}$ I and II\n- C.$\\hspace{1em}$ I and III\n- D.$\\hspace{1em}$ I, II and III\n',
