    content:
      '\n- Outline the features of cells that do not conform to the cell theory.\t\t\t<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Use named species to explain how unicellular organisms carry out processes of life.\t<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Compare and contrast the structure of prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells.\t\t<span class="marks">[8]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Any three from the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ mature red blood cells do not have a nucleus\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ striated muscle cells have many nuclei\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ giant algal cells can be seen without a microscope OR giant algal cells are very large <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ aseptate fungal hyphae OR fungal hyphae OR Mucor are multinucleate \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ phloem sieve tube elements lack nuclei OR do not have many organelles OR have continuous cytoplasm flowing through adjacent cells OR have sieve tube elements to provide metabolic support OR are interconnected cells.\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nMature red blood cells do not have a nucleus ($\\checkmark$), mature sieve tube elements do not have a nucleus ($\\checkmark$) and striated muscle cells and fungal hyphae have many nuclei ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any four of the following characteristics and a correct way the chosen unicellular organism carries out that process:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ cilia allow movement in Paramecium OR flagella allow movement in Chlamydomonas OR any other suitable mode of movement relevant to a named unicellular organism <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ contractile vacuole helps to regulate water potential of the cell OR contractile vacuole has a role in homeostasis in Paramecium OR contractile vacuole helps to regulate water potential of the cell OR contractile vacuole has a role in homeostasis in Chlamydomonas OR any other mechanism of homeostasis that is relevant to a named unicellular organism\t\t <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ oral groove allows nutrition in Paramecium OR nutrition is by photosynthesis in Chlamydomonas OR correct mode of nutrition for a named unicellular organism\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ Paramecium can reproduce asexually by binary fission OR Paramecium can reproduce by conjugation OR Chlorella produce asexually by mitosis\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ anal groove allows excretion in Paramecium OR excretion is by contractile vacuoles in Chlamydomonas OR correct mode of excretion for a named unicellular organism\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ growth of Paramecium occurs after cell division OR Chlamydomonas grows before and after cell division  OR correct mode of growth for a named unicellular organism\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ Paramecium sense their environment and respond by movement due to the movement of cilia OR Chlamydomonas have an eyespot to detect light OR correct example of sensitivity for a named unicellular organism\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>4 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nParamecia are unicellular organisms that can carry out all functions of life. Paramecia have cilia that allow movement ($\\checkmark$). Metabolic reactions ($\\checkmark$) happen in mitochondria and the cytoplasm. The contractile vacuole helps to regulate the water concentration ($\\checkmark$) of Paramecium by releasing excess water. The oral groove takes in food, so it is responsible for nutrition ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any eight of the following: \nAnswer must include at least one similarity and one difference\n  Similarities: \n$\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic AND eukaryotic cells have plasma membranes\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic AND eukaryotic cells have cytoplasm\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic AND eukaryotic cells have ribosomes\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic AND eukaryotic cells have genetic material OR DNA OR RNA\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  \n  Differences: \n$\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells are not compartmentalised  BUT eukaryotic cells are compartmentalised\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells do not have membrane-bound organelles BUT eukaryotic cells do have membrane-bound organelles\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells have DNA in a loop OR plasmid BUT eukaryotes have linear DNA OR chromosomes \t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells have 70S ribosomes BUT eukaryotic cells have 80S ribosomes\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells do not have a true nucleus OR have a nucleoid region BUT eukaryotic cells do have a true nucleus\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ all prokaryotic cells have a cell wall BUT not all eukaryotic cells have a cell wall\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic DNA is naked OR not associated with proteins BUT eukaryotic DNA is associated with histone proteins\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells are smaller THAN eukaryotic cells\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>8 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nProkaryotic and eukaryotic cells have genetic material ($\\checkmark$). Prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells have plasma membranes ($\\checkmark$). Prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells have cytoplasm ($\\checkmark$). Prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells have ribosomes ($\\checkmark$), but prokaryotes have 70S ribosomes, whereas eukaryotic cells have 80S ribosomes ($\\checkmark$). Prokaryotic cells do not have a true nucleus, but eukaryotic cells do have a true nucleus ($\\checkmark$). Prokaryotic cells do not have membrane-bound organelles but eukaryotic cells do have membrane-bound organelles such as mitochondria ($\\checkmark$). Prokaryotic cells have DNA in a loop but eukaryotic cells have linear DNA ($\\checkmark$). Not all eukaryotic cells have a cell wall but all prokaryotic cells do have a cell wall ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\nA quality mark is awarded if each part of the question (a, b, c) is answered to earn at least half of the points available, answers do not require re-reading to be understood, and there are almost no errors and little irrelevant information. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n',
