    selection: 'Selection A',
    type: 'ERQ',
    title: 'Question 72',
    content:
      '\n- Outline the role of auxin in positive phototropism.\t<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Explain the evidence that supports the theory that eukaryotic cells evolved from prokaryotic cells.\t<span class="marks">[5]</span>\n\n- Explain how the products of the light-dependent stage of photosynthesis are used in the light-independent stage to convert carbon dioxide into organic substances.\t<span class="marks">[7]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Any three of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ light is detected by group of proteins OR phototropins which trigger the movement of auxins by active transport\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ auxin efflux pumps move auxin so the concentration of auxins is more on the shadier side\nand lesser on the side with more light\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ plant cells have auxin receptors <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ when auxin binds to these receptors ,transcription of genes for enzyme OR expansin\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ auxin causes movement of  hydrogen ions from cytoplasm into the cell walls\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ hydrogen ions and expansion OR enzyme loosens cellulose fibres OR fibres of cell wall \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ causes cells on the shaded side of shoot tip to elongate\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nLight is detected by phototropins and this triggers the movement of auxins by active transport ($\\checkmark$). Auxin efflux pumps move auxins from cytoplasm into cell walls, so that the concentration of auxin is more on the shadier side ($\\checkmark$) and less on the side with more light. When auxin binds to receptors on the cells,  genes for the enzyme expansin are expressed ($\\checkmark$). Expansin, and the pumping of protons from the cytoplasm into the cell wall cause the loosening of cellulose fibres ($\\checkmark$) in the cell walls, leading to  elongation of the cells ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any five of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ theory of endosymbiosis proposes that mitochondria OR chloroplasts have evolved from free-living prokaryotes that were engulfed OR taken in by endocytosis, by larger cells\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ mitochondria OR chloroplasts have naked DNA\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ mitochondria OR chloroplasts divide by binary fission \t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ mitochondria OR chloroplasts divide independently of cell cycle OR cell \t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ mitochondria OR chloroplasts about same size as prokaryotes \t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ mitochondria OR chloroplasts have 70S ribosomes\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ mitochondria OR chloroplasts can synthesise their own proteins\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ mitochondria OR chloroplasts have double membranes \t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ mitochondria OR chloroplasts have inner membrane like OR similar in structure to prokaryotes AND outer membrane like OR similar in structure to eukaryotes\n<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ DNA of mitochondria OR chloroplasts is more closely related OR more similar to prokaryotic DNA than to nuclear DNA of eukaryotic cells, OR rRNA OR ribosomal RNA more closely related OR more similar to prokaryotes than eukaryotes\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ observations of modern examples of endosymbiosis OR given examples of present day endosymbiosis, provide support for the theory \t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  <span class="marks">[<strong>5 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe endosymbiotic theory supports the evidence that mitochondria and chloroplasts in eukaryotic cells evolved from prokaryotic cells, which were taken in by larger cells through endocytosis ($\\checkmark$). The evidence supporting this theory includes the fact that these organelles have naked DNA ($\\checkmark$), divide by binary fission ($\\checkmark$), can synthesise their own proteins ($\\checkmark$) and have double membranes around the outside ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any seven of the following: (drawing showing the Calvin cycle with the steps described below):\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ products of the light-dependent reaction are essential for the light-independent reactions  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ light-dependent reactions produce ATP, NADPH and oxygen\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ ATP and NADPH are used in the light-independent reactions OR Calvin cycle\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ light-independent reactions convert carbon dioxide into glucose and other organic molecules\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ enzyme RuBisCO fixes carbon dioxide\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ causes 1 x RuBP to bind to 1 x carbon dioxide\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ 6 C compound is unstable and forms two 3C compounds of glycerate-3-phosphate OR GP\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ ATP and NADPH are used to convert glycerate-3-phosphate OR GP to triose phosphate OR TP\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ some of the triose phosphate OR TP leaves the cycle to form carbohydrates, most is used to reform RuBP <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ regeneration of RuBP requires energy in the form of ATP\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>7 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nLight-dependent reactions of photosynthesis produce ATP, NADPH ($\\checkmark$) and oxygen. Oxygen is a by-product, ATP and NADPH are used in the light-independent reactions. In the stroma of the chloroplast, carbon dioxide combines with RuBP ($\\checkmark$), a 5C compound catalysed by the enzyme Rubisco ($\\checkmark$). The 6C compound formed is unstable and splits into two molecules of glycerate-3-phosphate ($\\checkmark$).\n  ATP and NADPH ($\\checkmark$) are used to convert glycerate-3-phosphate into triose phosphate ($\\checkmark$). Some of the molecules of triose phosphate leave the cycle to form glucose ($\\checkmark$) or other carbohydrates, most of it is used to regenerate the 5C RuBP ($\\checkmark$). Regeneration of RuBP again requires ATP ($\\checkmark$) obtained from the light-dependent reactions.\n\n$\\underline{\\textrm{For additional detail}}$:  see 5:26 in Photosynthesis Key Concept Video: https://www.revisionvillage.com/ib-biology/hl/key-concepts/?keyConceptId=cd710a11-a37d-4f93-aed3-30e4e1d75e55\n\nA quality mark is awarded if each part of the question (a, b, c) is answered to earn at least half of the points available, answers do not require re-reading to be understood, and there are almost no errors and little irrelevant information. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n',
