    content:
      '\n- Outline the binomial naming system and its importance. \t<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Explain how a sample of cells taken from a foetus can be used to determine whether the foetus will be biologically male or biologically female at birth.\t\t<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Outline the outcomes of the human genome project and their impacts on different fields of science. <span class="marks">[7]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Any four of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ binomial naming system as the system used to name species \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ genus name and species name \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ species with the same genus share many characteristics OR are closely related\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ internationally agreed\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ facilitates understanding and communication between scientists \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>4 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe binomial naming system is the system which scientists use to name species ($\\checkmark$) and this is internationally agreed ($\\checkmark$), which means it’s used all over the world, which aids in the communication between scientists ($\\checkmark$) in different countries. The name of each species has two parts, the first highlights the genus to which it belongs and the second part refers to the species ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any four of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ cells grown in a culture medium <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ cells stained <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ observed under a light microscope <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ photomicrograph taken during mitosis OR mitotic metaphase <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ chromosomes arranged according to size OR position of centromeres <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ look at chromosome pair 23 <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ two large chromosomes mean foetus is XX <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ one large chromosome and one small chromosome means foetus is XY <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ XX is biologically female AND XY is biologically male <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>4 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nOnce the sample of cells has been taken from the foetus they are grown in a culture medium ($\\checkmark$). They are then stained ($\\checkmark$) and observed under a light microscope ($\\checkmark$). A photomicrograph is taken ($\\checkmark$), and the image is cut up so that the chromosomes can be arranged by size and position of the centromere ($\\checkmark$). A foetus with two large X chromosomes will be biologically female ($\\checkmark$), and a foetus with one large X and one small Y chromosome will be biologically male ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any seven of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the Human Genome Project (HGP) sequenced the entire human genome\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ it determined the total number of base pairs in the human genome\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ it estimated the number of genes in the human genome \t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ identified the loci of genes\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ identified repeat sequences \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ identified locations of single nucleotide polymorphisms\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ identified gene sequences associated with certain diseases OR biological processes OR traits\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ HGP stimulated further development OR reduced the price of sequencing technology\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ technology developed for the HGP is now used to diagnose diseases OR identify micro-organisms OR DNA matching in forensics and medicine OR genetic modification  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ contributed to the field by identifying genetic markers that affect how individuals metabolise and respond to medications OR contribute information for personalised medicine\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ insights into evolutionary relationships OR genetic similarities OR genetic differences <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ identification of regulatory elements OR non-coding RNAs OR components that play essential roles in gene expression OR cellular function  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ emphasised importance of consideration of ethical OR legal OR social implications of genomic research  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>7 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe Human Genome Project (HGP) sequenced the entire human genome ($\\checkmark$), identified the loci of genes ($\\checkmark$) and identified gene sequences that are connected to some diseases ($\\checkmark$) such as breast cancer. Locations of single nucleotide polymorphisms ($\\checkmark$) were discovered which are variations in individuals DNA base pairs. The results have contributed to the development of personalised medicine ($\\checkmark$) as genetic markers have been identified that affect how individuals respond to medications. The technology developed for the HGP has led to further advancements in technology, reducing the cost of genetic sequencing ($\\checkmark$).  The HGP also emphasised how important it is to consider the ethical implications ($\\checkmark$) of genomic research and the importance of informed consent.\n\n\nA quality mark is awarded if each part of the question (a, b, c) is answered to earn at least half of the points available, answers do not require re-reading to be understood, and there are almost no errors and little irrelevant information. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n',
