      'The Eurasian beaver (Castor fiber) has been described as a species that promotes biodiversity. Beavers are herbivores that feed on freshwater plants and tree bark. They use their sharp front teeth to fell trees and use the logs and branches to build dams that create pools in which they can build their lodge. A beaver lodge is a construction in which they nest and raise their young, providing protection from predators.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/137391ca-319d-43a2-9119-cf4e9aa52801/images/0716c3a5-4515-4c2c-9098-2dc170bfb110/BI1684%20fig1.png)\n\n\r\n[Source: Jerzy Strzelecki, retrieved July 2024 from https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File: Castor_fiber_07(js),_Narew_River,\r\n_Poland.jpg, copyright under CC BY-SA 3.0]\n\n\n- Suggest ways in which the reintroduction of beavers can increase biodiversity. <span class="marks">[4]</span>  \n\nThe effect of introducing beavers on the species diversity of birds and bats was studied in four areas: on river banks, one without any beaver activity and one where beavers are present, and then ponds, again, one without beaver activity and one where beavers were present. The graph below shows the calculated Simpson’s reciprocal index of Diversity for each area.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/137391ca-319d-43a2-9119-cf4e9aa52801/images/536e088c-9e87-4ae5-902d-c81de6be0cb0/BI1684%20fig2.png)\n\n\r\n[©Revision Village 2024]\n\n\n- State two necessary measurements to calculate Simpson’s reciprocal index of diversity.\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n- Calculate the percentage increase in the species diversity of bats in the pond after the introduction of the beaver.\t<span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n\nBeavers became extinct in the UK over 400 years ago. Reintroduction programmes are now being carried out in various regions of the UK.\n\n- Suggest three anthropogenic activities that could have led to the extinction of the beavers in the UK. <span class="marks">[3]</span>  \n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- any four of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ many different habitats OR niches are created by beaver activity\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ dams create pools that slow the run-off of rivers, benefiting plant rooting\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ dams generate wetlands that harbour insect OR invertebrate species\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ this promotes a food chain with consumers such as birds\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ pools are habitats for aquatic plants OR fish\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ felling trees allows sunlight onto the forest floor, benefiting ground-level plants and shrubs\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ fallen trees are a source of food for microorganisms OR detritivores\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n<span class="marks">[<strong>4 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe activity of beavers creates many habitats for other organisms ($\\checkmark$), with an overall increase in biodiversity. For example, the felling of trees opens up patches of ground to sunlight, promoting ground-level vegetation ($\\checkmark$). The pools created by beaver dams attract insects ($\\checkmark$) and the consumers (such as birds) that feed on those insects ($\\checkmark$). Dams slow the run-off of rainwater which has a beneficial effect on plant roots which are not washed away by fast-flowing water ($\\checkmark$). The pools also attract fish species and aquatic plants that can oxygenate the pond water ($\\checkmark$); beavers do not eat fish, so there is no harm to the fish from them.\n\n\n\n- the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ total number of different species in the area OR species richness AND  total number of organisms of each species OR species evenness\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n<span class="marks">[<strong>1 mark maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nTwo measurements needed to calculate Simpson’s Diversity Index are the total number of species in the area and the total number of organisms of each species($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ percentage increase = {(final volume - initial volume)/initial volume} $\\times$ 100%\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\nOR {(0.81-0.51) / 0.51} $\\times$ 100%\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ 58.8%   (allow numbers between 52 and 64%) <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n<span class="marks">[<strong>2 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nPercentage increase = {(p.81$-$0.51) / 0.51} x 100% ($\\checkmark$)\n  = $-$58.8% ($\\checkmark$)\n\n\n\n- any three of the following:\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ hunting for fur OR castoreum\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ habitat destruction OR the draining of wetlands OR other hydrological changes\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ deforestation OR logging OR increase in agricultural land\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ water pollution\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ fragmentation of landscape\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ urbanisation  OR industrial development OR road construction\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ introduction of alien species\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ trade OR travel leading to introduction of disease\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ use of pesticides OR herbicides OR agricultural chemicals\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n<span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe extinction of beavers in the UK may have been caused by overhunting for their valuable fur and castoreum ($\\checkmark$), combined with extensive habitat destruction due to the draining of wetlands ($\\checkmark$) and deforestation for agricultural expansion ($\\checkmark$). Additionally, the introduction of non-native species ($\\checkmark$) and diseases, through international travel, ($\\checkmark$) further contributed to their decline.\n',
