      "Refer to the diagram showing a section of a DNA strand.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/cda96db5-d1f8-4821-bfb9-ddd33e4caa82/images/af63cd61-e4b6-436d-853c-27b1cbae8bda/Picture1.png)\n\n\n[© Revision Village 2025. Created in BioRender.com]\n\nWhich carbon on the deoxyribose sugar is bonded to the phosphate group in the phosphodiester bond?\n\n\n\n- A.  Carbon 1'\n- B.  Carbon 2'\n- C.  Carbon 3'\n- D.  Carbon 4'\n",
    markScheme:
      "C\n\n$\\underline{\\textrm{Explanation}}$:\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/cda96db5-d1f8-4821-bfb9-ddd33e4caa82/images/a1f3dc2e-b1f0-4602-a55b-087562538587/ANS.png)\n\n\nThe phosphodiester bond forms between the 3' carbon of the sugar in one nucleotide (which has an –OH group), and the 5' phosphate group of the next nucleotide. So, the 3' carbon is directly involved in forming the bond that links nucleotides within a single strand of DNA or RNA, making Choice C correct.\nThe 1' carbon of the sugar is the attachment point for the nitrogenous base, not for the phosphate group; Choice A is incorrect.\nIn deoxyribose, the 2' carbon lacks an –OH group (it has just –H), distinguishing DNA from RNA.  It is not involved in bonding to phosphate, so Choice B is incorrect.\nThe 4' carbon connects to the 3' carbon and the 5' carbon within the sugar ring, but does not form bonds with the phosphate group; Choice D is incorrect.",
