      'DNA and RNA are nucleic acids that are essential to all living organisms.\n\n- Draw and label a diagram of a nucleotide.\t <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Explain how the variation in base sequences leads to the ability of DNA to have an enormous capacity for storing genetic information.\t<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- DNA is a polymer of nucleotides. Describe the structure of DNA.  \t<span class="marks">[7]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ phosphate group drawn as a circle in correct place.  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ ribose sugar drawn as a pentagon in correct place <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ nitrogenous base drawn as a rectangle in correct place <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ all three parts labelled correctly <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  Bonds and names of nitrogenous bases do not need to be labelled\n<span class="marks">[<strong>4 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$:\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/9150aae9-afb7-4f8c-ad8a-a689af882f11/images/e2a45c02-e188-4e34-a535-699a939168c7/BI1047.png)\n\n\n[© Revision village 2022]\n\n\n\n- any four of the following (there must be at least one similarity and one difference given to gain full marks):\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ genetic code is stored in the sequence of nitrogenous bases <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ three bases OR a codon, codes for one amino acid <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ 64 codons but only 20 amino acids OR degenerate code <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ complementary base pairing <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ for each extra nucleotide along a DNA strand, the number of possible combinations of bases increases exponentially <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ mutations introduce new genetic information <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ certain sequences are conserved across species because they encode vital information  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ DNA molecules can be hundreds of millions of base pairs long OR DNA molecules are very long <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ non-coding regions have regulatory functions, contributing to the complexity of gene expression and overall genetic information <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>4 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe genetic code resides within the sequences of nitrogenous bases ($\\checkmark$) along a DNA molecule. Amino acids are coded for by codons ($\\checkmark$), and the code is degenerate ($\\checkmark$), in other words, some amino acids are coded for by more than one codon. The longer the DNA molecule, the greater the number of possible combinations of bases along the DNA strand, in fact there is an exponential increase in possibilities ($\\checkmark$) for each single nucleotide added to the polymer. Mutations also add to the variety ($\\checkmark$) of the genetic code.\n\n\n\n- any seven of the following: \n(appropriately labelled and correctly drawn DNA segment can be used in the answer)\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ DNA is a double helix \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ two strands are anti-parallel OR parallel but in opposite directions OR one strand is in the 5’ to 3’ direction and the other strand is in the 3’ to 5’ direction\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ strands are twisted OR right-handed and turn into a double helix with around 10 base pairs per turn\t <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ nucleotides consist of one phosphate group, one deoxyribose sugar and one nitrogenous base\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ phosphate group is bound to the 5’ carbon of the sugar OR deoxyribose OR pentose   \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ phosphate group is bound to the 3’ carbon OH group of deoxyribose (of the next nucleotide)\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ covalent OR phosphodiester bond between phosphate and the sugar\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ nitrogenous base OR base is bound to the 1’ carbon of the sugar OR deoxyribose OR pentose sugar <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ covalent bond between nitrogenous base and deoxyribose OR sugar OR pentose sugar \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ two strands are held together by hydrogen bonds between nitrogen bases of two nucleotides OR 3 hydrogen bonds between guanine and cytosine OR 2 hydrogen bonds between adenine and thymine\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ A pairs up with T AND C pairs up with G\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>7 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nDNA is a nucleic acid, also known as a polymer of nucleotides. Many nucleotides are joined together to form it. One nucleotide consists of three parts; a phosphate group, deoxyribose sugar and a nitrogenous base ($\\checkmark$).\n  One end of the phosphate group is bonded to the 5’ carbon of the sugar ($\\checkmark$) through a condensation reaction. On the other side of the nucleotide, the phosphate group is bonded to the 3’ carbon sugar ($\\checkmark$) of another nucleotide through a condensation reaction. Both bonds are  covalent bonds ($\\checkmark$). Repeated alternating sugar-phosphate bonds form the sugar-phosphate backbone.  The 1’ carbon of the sugar is covalently bonded to the nitrogenous base ($\\checkmark$)also through a condensation reaction to make up one complete nucleotide.\n  DNA is a double helix ($\\checkmark$) in which nitrogenous bases form the centre of the structure, and both strands are held together by hydrogen bonds ($\\checkmark$) between the complementary bases from each strand. A pairs up with T, and C always pairs up with G ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\nA quality mark is awarded if each part of the question (a, b, c) is answered to earn at least half of the points available, answers do not require re-reading to be understood, and there are almost no errors and little irrelevant information. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n',
