      'Below is a diagram of a motor neuron. Neurons are the longest cells in the human body.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/7876a55e-0692-459c-a884-5c8979a6dd42/images/827ddc07-1d3d-43d2-a23e-f8f707d37a6c/BI0833A.png)\n\n\n[©Revision Village 2023. Created with BioRender.com]\n\n- Explain the factors that limit cell size in humans. \t<span class="marks">[4]</span>  \n\nBelow is a diagram of a Paramecium, a unicellular organism.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/7876a55e-0692-459c-a884-5c8979a6dd42/images/971509ed-990a-4f10-96a2-6c8d5a7a22a1/paramecium%20black.png)\n\n\n[©Revision Village 2023]\n\n- Explain how life functions are performed by Paramecium.\t<span class="marks">[4]</span>  \n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Any four of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ surface area affects the rate at which materials enter and leave the cell     <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ volume affects the rate at which materials are used and produced by the cell     <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the surface area to volume ratio affects the rate of metabolism in a cell     <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the bigger the cell, the smaller the SA ratio is\t  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ cells having a low SA ratio cannot exchange materials fast enough <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ some cells, OR motor neurons, OR muscle cells, OR other named example in humans, are long and thin, which maintains a high SA ratio\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>4 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample Answer}}$: \nThe surface area of a cell affects the rate at which materials enter and leave cells ($\\checkmark$). On the other hand, the cell’s volume affects the rate at which materials are used and produced ($\\checkmark$). A small surface area to volume ratio is not ideal for human cells because it limits the cell’s ability to export waste from the cytoplasm rapidly enough to meet the cytoplasm’s metabolic needs, such as the availability of oxygen ($\\checkmark$). A large cell has a small surface area to volume ratio ($\\checkmark$). Therefore, the transport of the substances is more efficient in small cells.\n\n\n\n- Any four of the following (function of life must be mentioned when explaining how Paramecium performs this, to award mark):\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ functions of life are metabolism AND growth AND reproduction AND nutrition AND homeostasis AND movement AND excretion AND response to stimuli, OR sensitivity  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ movement in Paramecium is demonstrated by cilia used to propel themselves through water\t <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ response is through reacting to stimuli in the environment OR avoidance of light <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ homeostasis is demonstrated by keeping the internal conditions within set limits OR excess water is expelled by the contractile vacuole \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ metabolism is carried out by enzymes in the cytoplasm    <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ growth is an irreversible increase in size OR dry mass and paramecium achieve this  through accumulating organic matter OR nutrients from food    <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ reproduction function in Paramecium is demonstrated by asexual division through binary fission, OR mitosis or micronucleus and amitotic division of macronucleus OR sexually through conjugation\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ excretion is the removal of metabolic waste products from the cell OR diffusion of CO2 out of the cell\t <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ nutrition is performed by ingesting smaller organisms and digesting them in vesicles OR through endocytosis    <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>4 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample Answer}}$: \nParamecium acquires nutrients by ingesting bacteria and digesting them in vesicles($\\checkmark$). It exhibits growth when it irreversibly increases in size by accumulating organic matter from ingested food ($\\checkmark$). Paramecium responds to different environmental stimuli. For example, it changes the direction of its movement once it touches a solid object ($\\checkmark$). Excretion in Paramecium occurs when waste products such as carbon dioxide diffuse out of the cell ($\\checkmark$). Paramecium reproduces both asexually by binary fission ($\\checkmark$).\n',
