    content:
      '\n- Outline the different uses of karyograms. <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Distinguish between cells with haploid and diploid nuclei. <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Compare and contrast different types of chromosomes. <span class="marks">[8]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Any three of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ karyograms are images of the chromosomes in an organism <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ homologous chromosomes are arranged in pairs of decreasing length OR Sex chromosomes are the 23rd pair in human karyograms\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ karyograms can be used to identify the sex of an individual\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ karyograms can be used to identify conditions caused by trisomy, e.g. Down syndrome OR Patau syndrome OR Klinefelter syndrome\t \t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ karyograms can be used to determine if a chromosome is missing OR if part of a chromosome is missing\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  <span class="marks">[<strong>3 mark maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  \n$\\underline{\\textrm{Sample Answer}}$: \nKaryograms ($\\checkmark$) are images of the chromosomes in an organism. In a karyogram, the pairs of homologous chromosomes are arranged in pairs of decreasing length ($\\checkmark$). The sex chromosomes are shown as the 23rd pair in human karyograms.\nKaryograms can be used to determine if an individual is a biological male or female ($\\checkmark$). Two X chromosomes are present in a human female cell, and one X chromosome and one Y chromosome are present in a human male cell.\nKaryograms can be used to identify conditions caused by trisomy (three copies of a chromosome) e.g. Down syndrome, Patau syndrome, Edward’s syndrome and Klinefelter syndrome).\n\n\n\n- Any four of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ haploid nuclei have one set of chromosomes, OR one chromosome per type WHEREAS diploid nuclei have two sets OR two chromosomes of each type <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ haploid nuclei have one allele for each gene WHEREAS diploid nuclei have two alleles for each gene <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ haploid nuclei in humans have 23 chromosomes, and diploid nuclei in humans have 46 chromosomes OR any other valid species example <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ haploid cells are usually gametes WHEREAS diploid cells are usually somatic cells <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ haploid cells are usually the result of meiosis, WHILE diploid cells are usually the result of mitosis.  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  <span class="marks">[<strong>4 mark maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  \n$\\underline{\\textrm{Sample Answer}}$: \nHaploid nuclei have one set of chromosomes($\\checkmark$), whereas diploid nuclei have two sets of chromosomes.  For example, in humans($\\checkmark$), gametes have 23 chromosomes, while somatic cells have 46 chromosomes. Haploid nuclei have one allele for each gene, ($\\checkmark$)  whereas diploid nuclei have two alleles for each gene. In humans, only gametes($\\checkmark$)  have haploid nuclei, whereas the rest of the somatic cells have diploid nuclei.\n\n\n\n- Any eight of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ (within one species) different chromosomes are composed of DNA molecules with different lengths\t <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ (within one species) different chromosomes have different numbers of genes\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ (within one species) different chromosomes have different types OR different numbers of genes <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ both prokaryotic AND eukaryotic chromosomes contain DNA\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ bacterial chromosomes are not associated with proteins, WHILE eukaryotic and archaeal chromosomes are associated with proteins <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic chromosomes are looped molecules of DNA, WHILE eukaryotic chromosomes are linear molecules of DNA <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH autosomes and sex chromosomes contain genes <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the human Y chromosome carries information mainly coding for male sex determination and development, WHILE the X chromosome carries information for other body characteristics <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ there is only one pair of sex chromosomes, WHILE there can be more than one pair of autosomes (in different species)\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ autosomes are pairs of homologous chromosomes of equal length, WHILE two sex chromosomes can be different lengths <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ chromosomes can be homologous and non-homologous <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ homologous chromosomes are pairs of chromosomes of equal length carrying the same genes, but different alleles, WHILE non-homologous chromosomes, carry different genes <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  <span class="marks">[<strong>8 mark maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  \n$\\underline{\\textrm{Sample Answer}}$: \nAll chromosomes are made of DNA and contain genes, but they differ in length ($\\checkmark$) and in the number of genes ($\\checkmark$) and type of genes ($\\checkmark$). Similarities and differences between prokaryotic and eukaryotic chromosomes: Both prokaryotic and eukaryotic chromosomes contain DNA ($\\checkmark$). Bacterial chromosomes are not associated with proteins, but eukaryotic chromosomes are associated with proteins ($\\checkmark$). Prokaryotic chromosomes are looped, while eukaryotic chromosomes are linear ($\\checkmark$).\n  Similarities and differences between autosomes and sex chromosomes: \nBoth autosomes and sex chromosomes are made of DNA and contain genes. Autosomes are chromosomes that do not determine sex and do not have genes for sex-linked characteristics; sex chromosomes determine sex and have genes for sex-linked traits. There is one pair of sex chromosomes in a somatic nucleus, but there can be more than one pair of autosomes ($\\checkmark$) in a somatic nucleus. X and Y chromosomes are of different lengths, while autosomal homologous chromosome pairs are equal in length ($\\checkmark$) \nComparing non-homologous chromosomes and homologous chromosomes:\nHomologous chromosomes are pairs of chromosomes that have genes for the same characteristics and can have the same or different alleles. Non-homologous chromosomes have genes for different characteristics ($\\checkmark$).\n  \n\nA quality mark is awarded if each part of the question (a, b, c) is answered to earn at least half of the points available, answers do not require re-reading to be understood, and there are almost no errors and little irrelevant information. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n',
