    selection: 'Selection B',
    type: 'ERQ',
    title: 'Question 57',
    content:
      '\n- Electron microscopy provides images of cells with significantly higher resolution when compared to light microscopy. Evaluate the implications and limitations of relying primarily on electron micrographs to understand cell function.\t\t\t<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Explain how advances in microscopy have contributed to our understanding of cell structure and function.\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Discuss the evidence for and against the idea that prokaryotic cells are “simple” compared to eukaryotic cells. \t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[8]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- any three of the following, must include at least one implication and one limitation\n  Implications\n$\\ce{ -> }$ fine detail resolution has led to a more detailed understanding of structure-function relationships\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ discovery of new organelles and structures\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  Limitations\n$\\ce{ -> }$ requires complex sample preparation\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ sample preparation can leave artefacts\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ samples must be fixed, dead, meaning no dynamic cellular processes can be observed\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ pigmentation or colour is not detected\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ maximum understanding comes from combining information from both light and electron microscopy\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  <span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nElectron microscopy gives us very detailed images, which let us see how the tiny parts of a cell are structured to fulfil their functions ($\\checkmark$). It has also led to the discovery of new things inside cells ($\\checkmark$). Unfortunately, to prepare specimens for electron microscopy, they must be treated in such a way that they are killed, and so we cannot observe processes happening in real time ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- any four of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ light microscopy allowed for the initial visualisation of cells and basic structures\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ staining techniques have enhanced the visibility of cell components\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ fluorescence microscopy enables visualisation and localisation of specific molecules \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ live-imaging techniques allow dynamic processes to be observed\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ electron microscopy provides significantly higher resolution than light microscopy\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ transmission electron microscopy reveals details of the internal structure of organelles\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ scanning electron microscopy provides 3-D images of cell surfaces OR cell shape\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  <span class="marks">[<strong>4 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nLight microscopy first allowed us to see cells and their basic parts ($\\checkmark$). Later, staining made it easier to see these parts more clearly ($\\checkmark$). Fluorescence microscopy has allowed scientists to visualise and pinpoint the locations of specific molecules within cells ($\\checkmark$).  Electron microscopy provides far greater resolution than light microscopy ($\\checkmark$), making it possible to see internal structures like mitochondria and membranes in fine detail ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- any eight of the following:\n  In favour\n$\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells lack membrane-bound organelles OR have less compartmentalisation\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells have a single, circular chromosome; eukaryotic cells have multiple linear chromosomes\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells are generally smaller\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells reproduce by binary fission, which is less complex than mitosis/meiosis\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  Against\n$\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells efficiently carry out all life processes within a single cell, demonstrating functional sophistication\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells exhibit diverse and complex metabolic pathways\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells exhibit unique metabolic pathways, ie chemosynthesis\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells can engage in cell signaling\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells have highly specialised adaptations (ie flagellae)\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells have a high surface area to volume ratio, increasing the exchange rate with the surroundings \t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic cells are structurally simpler but functionally complex\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ evaluation of the application of the word “simple”\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  <span class="marks">[<strong>8 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nProkaryotes are generally smaller ($\\checkmark$) than most eukaryotic cells, and they reproduce by binary fission ($\\checkmark$) instead of mitosis or meiosis. Prokaryotic cells are often called more simple than eukaryotic cells, but it is important to distinguish between structure and function ($\\checkmark$). Prokaryotic cells may appear simple, but they still carry out all of the functions of life ($\\checkmark$) and have some that are unique to prokaryotes. Although prokaryotes do not have membrane-bound organelles ($\\checkmark$), they still have complex metabolic pathways like cellular respiration and even pathways eukaryotes do not have, like chemosynthesis ($\\checkmark$). Prokaryotes can communicate with each other via cell signalling pathways like quorum sensing ($\\checkmark$) and also have highly specialised structures such as flagellae for motility ($\\checkmark$). The term “simple” is an oversimplification of a superficial observation.\n\n\nA quality mark is awarded if each part of the question (a, b, c) is answered to earn at least half of the points available, answers do not require re-reading to be understood, and there are almost no errors and little irrelevant information. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n',
