    content:
      'The table shows genome sizes for several different species.\nOrganismGenome Size (base pairs)Escherichia coli (Bacterium)5 millionSaccharomyces cerevisiae (Yeast)12 millionDrosophila melanogaster (Fruit Fly)140 millionXenopus laevis (Frog)????Homo sapiens3 billion\n\n\n- Describe the challenges of predicting the size of the genome of Xenopus laevis based on the information provided in the table. \t<span class="marks">[2]</span>  \n\n\nSingle-cell genome sequencing allows researchers to analyse the genetic material of individual cells. Cancer is characterised by significant genomic instability, leading to massive variations in genome size when compared to noncancerous cells.\n\n- Explain how single-cell genome sequencing can be more useful than traditional genome sequencing for developing effective cancer treatments.\t<span class="marks">[3]</span>  \n\n\nThe diagram below depicts nanopore DNA sequencing technology.  This portable technology involves passing a single piece of DNA through a tiny pore in a membrane in an electrical field in a manner such that the current can reveal the DNA sequence.  This allows for the analysis of environmental DNA (eDNA), which consists of DNA fragments shed by organisms into their surroundings (e.g., skin cells, waste).  It can also give almost immediate results for shorter fragments, and sequence entire genomes in as little as 3 days.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/bc9dbc7a-73a6-41de-bef4-c83dfff6f8fc/images/3d062db1-de82-446a-8141-4670a3bbbe8f/BI2802.png)\n\n\n[Source: Adapted from National Institutes of Standards and Technology (2024, November 18) DNA Sequencing Method [image]. Wikimedia Commons. Retrieved 04:53, May 5, 2025 from https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?title=File:DNA_Sequencing_Method_ (8051510835).jpg&oldid=958458868.Public Domain]\n\n- Discuss one potential benefit and one potential risk associated with the widespread use of portable DNA sequencing technologies. \t<span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- Suggest ways whole-genome sequencing can contribute to our understanding of evolutionary relationships between species, and also to personalised medicine. \t<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n',
