    content:
      'Which species are prioritised for conservation in the EDGE of Existence programme?\n\n\n\n- A.$\\hspace{1em}$ Species that are genetically distinct from other living species, and are in danger of extinction.\n- B.$\\hspace{1em}$ Species that are evolutionarily distinct, and are found in vulnerable ecosystems.\n- C.$\\hspace{1em}$ Species that are closely related to keystone species, and are in danger of extinction.\n- D.$\\hspace{1em}$ Species that are keystone species, and are found in vulnerable ecosystems.\n',
    markScheme:
      'A\n\n$\\underline{\\textrm{Explanation}}$: \nChoice A is correct because the EDGE of Existence program highlights and focuses on species that are evolutionarily distinct with few living relatives and, therefore, represent a disproportionately high level of genetic diversity. Additionally, the EDGE of Existence program only prioritises species on the endangered and vulnerable IUCN lists, which are, therefore, in danger of extinction.\nChoice B is incorrect because the EDGE of Existence program does not use vulnerable ecosystems as a criterion. It focuses solely on species that are evolutionarily distinct and threatened with extinction.\nChoice C is incorrect because while keystone species play a crucial role in maintaining ecosystem structure and function, they are not necessarily evolutionarily distinct. The EDGE programme does not prioritise species based on their ecological role.\nChoice D is incorrect because neither keystone species nor vulnerable ecosystems are criteria for the EDGE of Existence program.',
