    type: 'SAQ',
    title: 'Question 20',
    content:
      'Mountain gorillas (Gorilla beringei beringei)  were reclassified from "Critically Endangered" to "Endangered" by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) in November 2018. This change in status was a significant conservation success story, reflecting the positive impact of concerted efforts by governments, conservation organisations, and local communities to protect and increase the population of this subspecies of the eastern gorilla.\r\nThe table below shows the changes in the number of mountain gorillas from 2010 to 2018.\nYearNumber of gorillas2010480201660420181004\n\n\n- Calculate the percentage increase in the number of gorillas from 2010 to 2018.  <span class="marks">[1]</span>  \n- Although the mountain gorilla is rarely seen in zoos, another gorilla subspecies, the western lowland gorilla (Gorilla gorilla gorilla) is. Explain how zoos play a critical role in the conservation of endangered species. <span class="marks">[3]</span>  \n\nStudies have shown that the invasive plant species Sericostachys scandens affects forest composition and may affect the Grauer’s gorilla (Gorilla beringei graueri) recovery in Congo.\n\n- Outline two precautions that should be taken before considering biological control of invasive plants such as these.\t<span class="marks">[2]</span>  \n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- The following\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ 109.16% OR 109.2%\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n<span class="marks">[<strong>1 mark maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$:\n  $\\dfrac{(1004 - 480)}{480} \\times 100\\%$\n  = 109.16% ($\\checkmark$)\n- Any three of the following\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ animal husbandry facilities to help prevent death from disease or injury\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ maintain detailed records OR pedigrees OR known studbooks to track genetic lineage used to choose breeding pairs to maintain genetic diversity OR minimise inbreeding\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ exchange animals between different institutions to introduce new genetic diversity\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ captive breeding OR artificial insemination OR in vitro fertilisation increases chance of successful breeding OR means they do not have to find a mate\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$  reintroduction programs OR release animals into wild\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ scientists OR researchers can study the species up close OR in detail for greater understanding of how to protect it in-situ\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ educational programs to educate the public about the importance of animal conservation\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n<span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nZoos facilitate the exchange of animals between institutions ($\\checkmark$) and maintain detailed records to track genetic lineage used to choose breeding pairs to introduce new genetic diversity ($\\checkmark$).  Artificial insemination also increases the success rate of breeding ($\\checkmark$) endangered species. Moreover, zoos are instrumental in reintroducing programs that release animals back into the wild, directly contributing to restoring natural populations ($\\checkmark$) and ecosystems.\n- Any two of the following\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ research to make sure control organism specifically targets invasive species OR does not affect native species OR does not damage ecosystem OR habitats OR food chains\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ conditions in the target environment should support the survival of the control species\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ control species should have a natural control OR predator\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ control species should not spread outside the targeted area OR should not become an invasive species themselves\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ long-term monitoring plans to observe the effects of the biocontrol species\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ possible socio-economic impacts OR consider ethical OR cultural OR social implications of control species should be assessed\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n$\\ce{ -> }$ plan should be developed in case species need to be controlled OR eradicated <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\r\n<span class="marks">[<strong>2 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nBefore using biological control, it is crucial to conduct thorough research to ensure that the control organism specifically targets the invasive species without impacting native species or the ecosystem ($\\checkmark$). Additionally, the conditions in the target environment must support the survival of the control species ($\\checkmark$)\r\n, ensuring it can effectively reduce the invasive population without becoming invasive itself($\\checkmark$).\n',
