    content:
      'The graph below shows Biodiversity Intactness, a long-term indicator that measures how much original biodiversity remains within terrestrial communities on the continents, based on levels from around 1500 A.D., when records began.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/af00fec2-0075-40c9-8a41-072c06650376/images/1ad75b4e-1e66-416a-87f8-4d878e1c4179/BI2808%20-%20Bi2813%20A4.2%20PQ%20MCQ%20and%20SAQ%20PhilCh.jpeg.JPEG)\n\n\n[Source: adapted from WWF (2024) Living Planet Report 2024 – A System in\nPeril. WWF, Gland, Switzerland http://bit.ly/4jzPxrE. Retrieved 30 April 2025, Public Domain]\n\n\n- \n  - Using data from the graph, compare and contrast biodiversity in Asia and Europe.  <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n  - Suggest reasons for the difference(s) you highlighted in part (a) (i)   <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n\n- Outline two reasons why the graph might give an inexact picture of global biodiversity loss.  <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- Certain Asian species, including the Chinese Crocodile Lizard (Shinisaurus crocodilurus), have been selected for the EDGE of Existence programme in Asia, whereas another endangered species, the Asian elephant (Elephas maximus), is not on the EDGE of Existence list. Suggest why.  <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- \n  - any two of the following (must include one similarity and one difference to gain full marks)\n    Similarity:\n$\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH showed a high level (close to 1.0) in 1800    <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n    $\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH declined from 1800 to 1950  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n    $\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH showed an overall decline 1800 - 2024 OR in the period of study    <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n    Difference:\n$\\ce{ -> }$ Asia fell steeply from 1950-2000 WHEREAS Europe recovered in that period  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n    $\\ce{ -> }$ Asia continues to decline (in 2024) WHEREAS Europe is stable OR increasing   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n    <span class="marks">[<strong>2 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nA similarity is that both continents’ biodiversity fell from 1800 to 1950 ($\\checkmark$). By contrast, Europe’s biodiversity increased from 1950 onwards, whereas Asia’s continues to decline in the present day ‘any two of the following (must include one similarity and one difference to gain full marks) ($\\checkmark$).\n\n  \n  \n  - any three of the following:\n    $\\ce{ -> }$ better awareness OR education in Europe   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n    $\\ce{ -> }$ weaker environmental protection law in Asia <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n    $\\ce{ -> }$ less poverty OR more access to money to fund biodiversity work in Europe   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n    $\\ce{ -> }$ more reliance on subsistence farming in Asia   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n    $\\ce{ -> }$ less human population growth in Europe since 1950 OR high population density in Asia   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n    $\\ce{ -> }$ more deforestation OR urbanisation in Asia since 1950    <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n    $\\ce{ -> }$ European OR American companies operating in Asia; accept palm oil plantation <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n    $\\ce{ -> }$ theft OR trafficking OR poaching OR illegal wildlife trading OR of Asian native species   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n    $\\ce{ -> }$ conflict OR political instability in some Asian regions limits long-term biodiversity policy implementation   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n    $\\ce{ -> }$ higher rate of industrialisation OR infrastructure development in Asia since 1950  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n    accept converse arguments\n    <span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nAsia’s rapid economic growth and population growth have put pressure on natural resources ($\\checkmark$). An example could be the draining of wetlands and deforestation to create city space for housing ($\\checkmark$). Weaker laws and law enforcement in Asia ($\\checkmark$) have led to a rise in poaching and trafficking of endangered species, and this can lead to eventual extinction. Non-Asian companies have made large agricultural investments in Asia such as large-scale palm oil plantations, which damage the ecosystem in native tropical forest areas ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n\n- any two of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ only terrestrial ecosystems OR land are covered in the data OR there is no information on aquatic OR seas OR ocean ecosystems   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ there is no distinction between subcontinents such as North and South America    <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ there is no distinction between kingdoms OR between plants and animals OR microorganisms     <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ data collection in 1800 will have been less sophisticated OR accurate than 2024    <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ biodiversity in 1500 OR baseline data was already influenced by human activity   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ indicator may rely on modelled OR estimated data rather than direct field measurements   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  <span class="marks">[<strong>2 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe data only covers terrestrial ecosystems, so takes no account of aquatic organisms ($\\checkmark$). Also, methods of measuring biodiversity in 2024 will be a lot more accurate than those used in previous centuries ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- any three of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the elephant has close genetic relatives OR more close relatives (than the crocodile)   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the lizard is more evolutionarily unique (than the elephant)   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ conservation data on the elephant is insufficient OR not up-to-date (to qualify for EDGE)      <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the elephant may not be globally endangered OR it may be endangered in one country only OR have a healthy population in other countries   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ there is better ex-situ conservation OR better global zoo OR captive populations of the elephant than the  lizard    <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ lizard may occupy a more restricted OR fragmented habitat, increasing extinction risk   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  <span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe Chinese crocodile lizard may be very distinct genetically from its nearest relative, which gives it priority for selection into the EDGE programme, whereas the elephant has more close relatives ($\\checkmark$). The elephant is a popular species for zoos and conservation projects, so there will be higher populations in captivity ($\\checkmark$), making its extinction risk lower. Also, the elephant may be endangered in one country but may exist in large populations elsewhere, lowering its risk of global extinction danger ($\\checkmark$).\n',
